# migrated from tests/cases/correction.chat (gen346, hermetic + isolated;
# expectations aligned to current behaviour).
[mock hermetic]
!set PARROT0_BASE=
!set PARROT0_SESSION=
!set PARROT0_WORLD_FACTS=0
!set PARROT0_LANG=en
!reset

[test correction]
# gen218 (docs/plans/the-linguistic-glue.md, G2 — correction pull): integrating a
# later correction as DETERMINISTIC glue, not an emergent field. A turn opening
# with the correction marker "no" before a negative claim ("no, socrates is not a
# man") is the user OVERRIDING a belief stated earlier. The marker is peeled and
# the negation re-dispatched with a correction flag set, so the standing positive
# is retracted (across every layer — even a curated/base fact) and the conclusion
# re-derives cleanly. Before this, the leading "no," made the whole turn fall into
# not-understood; now the correction is parsed and integrated. EN + IT (the
# bilingual ratchet): "no" opens a correction in both, and the negation parser
# already serves both word orders (gen44). The override of a CURATED base fact is
# exercised by `make glue-bench` (corr-en/it), which runs with the full KB.

> socrates is a man
< Learned: man(socrates).
> is socrates a man
< Yes.
> no, socrates is not a man
< Learned: not man(socrates).
> is socrates a man
< No.
# Italian: same marker, same flip (the negation parser is order-insensitive).
> tweety è un uccello
< Learned: bird(tweety).
> no, tweety non è un uccello
< Learned: not bird(tweety).
> è tweety un uccello?
< No.
